TOTAL_PAGES: 1: United Therapeutics Announces FREEDOM-EV Study Of Orenitram® To Continue As Planned Following Interim Analysis
column7: SILVER SPRING, Md. and RESEARCH TRIANGLE PARK, N.C., Sept. 7, 2017 /PRNewswire/ -- United Therapeutics Corporation (UTHR) today announced that the independent data monitoring committee (DMC) for the FREEDOM-EV study of Orenitram (treprostinil) extended-release tablets had completed a pre-specified interim safety and efficacy analysis.  The DMC did not identify any new safety concerns associated with Orenitram therapy, and recommended that the trial be continued as planned without modification.  FREEDOM-EV is a Phase 3, international, multi-center, randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled, clinical worsening study of Orenitram in patients with pulmonary arterial hypertension (PAH) receiving background oral monotherapy study (a phosphodiesterase type 5 inhibitor or an endothelin receptor antagonist).

TOTAL_PAGES: 1: United Therapeutics reworks deal ahead of a key patent's expiration
column7: Silver Spring drugmaker United Therapeutics Corp. extended an exclusive license with drug giant Eli Lilly & Co. to cover its pulmonary hypertension drug Adcirca, which will lose part of its patent protection later this year.  The active ingredient in Adcirca is tadalafil, also the active pharmaceutical ingredient in Cialis, which is marketed by Eli Lilly (LLY) to treat erectile dysfunction.  United Therapeutics (UTHR), in 2008, acquired the commercial rights to Adcirca from Eli Lilly for the treatment of pulmonary hypertension — but one of three patents held by the larger company that protects Adcirca is set to expire in November.

TOTAL_PAGES: 1: These Greater Washington companies may be most affected by Trump's tax reform
column7: President Donald Trump introduced his much-anticipated tax reform plan  Wednesday, aimed at simplifying the tax code for individuals and lowering tax rates for businesses.  Key provisions of the proposal include paring down the number of tax brackets for wage earners from seven to three — of 10 percent, 25 percent and 35 percent — and a lowering of corporate tax rates from 35 percent to 15 percent.  The Trump document has one line that reads, “Territorial tax system to level the playing field for American companies.” Ostensibly, that would mean taxing U.S. companies only on profits earned in the United States instead of assessing a tax on all their profits earned around the globe, CNN reported.

Martine Rothblatt, CEO of United Therapeutics, says the goal is to manufacture organs from human cells that can be transplanted into patients.

TOTAL_PAGES: 1: United Therapeutics loses challenge to its drug patent
column7: Silver Spring-based biotech United Therapeutics Corp. (UTHR) lost a recent challenge to one of its lead patents for its flagship drugs.  The U.S. Patent and Trademark Office's Patent Trial and Appeal Board found that all of the company's claims for the particular patent — which impacts its lead products for treating pulmonary arterial hypertension such as Remodulin, Tyvaso and Orenitram — are not patentable.  In a statement, United Therapeutics officials said they are evaluating all of their options, including possibly appealing the decision in the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit or requesting a rehearing before the patent board.

United Therapeutics has been working with Medtronic, Inc. to develop Medtronic's proprietary intravascular infusion catheter to be used with Medtronic's implantable infusion pump and related infusion system components (together referred to as the Implantable System for Remodulin, or RemoSynch) for the delivery of Remodulin to treat patients with pulmonary arterial hypertension.

(UTHR) blames increasing competition in the pulmonary arterial hypertension space for its lower-than-expected revenue last year, CEO Martine Rothblatt told analysts Wednesday.  During the Silver Spring-based company's fourth-quarter earnings call, Rothblatt said there has been weaker growth for some of its drugs — Orenitram, Tyvaso and Remodulin.  Patients are sticking with alternative therapies, such as a combination of Adcirca with Letairis, longer than expected before switching to its products, she said.
